<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-intersecting-secants-and-tangents" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Intersecting Secants and Tangents</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurement and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Circles, Chords and Tangents
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Determine the length of intersecting chords and tangent to a circle
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        11
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    12 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To lead learners to discover that the products of secant segments from the same external point are equal, and that this product equals the square of the tangent from that point.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Circulate as groups measure and compute. If a group's products are quite different, ask them to re-measure carefully — small errors in drawing the secant near the circle can skew the external segment. Once groups have results, ask: <em>"What do you notice about your two products? And how does PT² compare?"</em> Resist confirming the answer until groups have shared with each other.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity xml:id="activity-secant-tangent-discovery">
        <statement>
            <p>
                For this activity you will need plain paper, a ruler, a pencil, and a circular object such as the base of a tin or bottle.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Place your circular object on the paper and trace carefully around it to draw a circle. Label its centre <m>O</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Mark a point <m>P</m> clearly outside the circle, at least 3 cm from the nearest point of the circle.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a straight line from <m>P</m> that crosses through the circle, entering at one point (<m>A</m>) and leaving at another (<m>B</m>). A line like this, which cuts a circle at two points, is called a <term>secant</term>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Draw a second secant from <m>P</m>, going in a different direction, and label its two crossing points <m>C</m> (nearer to <m>P</m>) and <m>D</m> (farther from <m>P</m>).
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Measure the four distances <m>PA</m>, <m>PB</m>, <m>PC</m>, <m>PD</m> in millimetres. Record them in a table and calculate the two products:
                            <md>
                                PA \times PB \qquad \text{and} \qquad PC \times PD.
                            </md>
                            What do you notice?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Learners should find <m>PA \times PB \approx PC \times PD</m>. Small measurement errors are expected; differences of up to 5% are acceptable with careful drawing. The key result is that the two products are approximately equal.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Now draw a line from <m>P</m> that <em>just touches</em> the circle at exactly one point — a tangent. Label the point of tangency <m>T</m>. Measure the length <m>PT</m>.
                        </p>
                        <note component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Learners may need a moment to get the tangent right. Remind them that a tangent touches at one point only — it should not enter the circle. Rotating a ruler slowly around <m>P</m> until it just grazes the circle works well.
                            </p>
                        </note>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Calculate <m>PT^2</m>. How does it compare with <m>PA \times PB</m>?
                        </p>
                        <solution component="lesson-plan">
                            <p>
                                Learners should find <m>PT^2 \approx PA \times PB \approx PC \times PD</m>.
                            </p>
                        </solution>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Compare your results with another group. Do they get the same products even though they used a different external point <m>P</m>? What conjecture can you make?
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Suggested Time</title>
                    <p>
                        15 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Objective</title>
                    <p>
                        To formalise the two-secant and tangent-secant theorems and develop learners' fluency in applying them.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Confirm the results from the activity. Write on the board: <m>PA \times PB = PC \times PD = PT^2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Introduce the vocabulary: a <em>secant</em> is a line that crosses a circle at two points; the <em>external segment</em> of a secant from point <m>P</m> is the part from <m>P</m> to the nearer intersection.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <title>Two-Secant Theorem</title>
        <p>
            A <term>secant</term> to a circle is a straight line that intersects the circle at two distinct points.
        </p>
    
        <figure xml:id="fig-two-secant-theorem">
            <caption>Two secants from external point <m>P</m>.</caption>
            <image width="60%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/P, 4/0/O}
                        \tkzDefCircle[R](O,2) \tkzGetPoint{cR}
                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                        \tkzDefPoint(6.5,2){S1}
                        \tkzInterLC[near](P,S1)(O,cR) \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}
                        \tkzDefPoint(6.5,-1.5){S2}
                        \tkzInterLC[near](P,S2)(O,cR) \tkzGetPoints{C}{D}
                        \tkzDrawSegments(P,B P,D)
                        \tkzDrawPoints(P,A,B,C,D)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](C)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](D)
                        \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, pos=0.2, font=\small](P,B){$PA$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, pos=0.55, font=\small](P,B){$PB$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, pos=0.2, font=\small](P,D){$PC$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, pos=0.55, font=\small](P,D){$PD$}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
                    
        <p> If two secants are drawn to a circle from the same external point <m>P</m>, with one secant meeting the circle at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> and the other meeting the circle at <m>C</m> and <m>D</m>, then
            <md>
                PA \times PB = PC \times PD.
            </md>
            In words: <em>the product of the external segment and the whole secant is the same for both secants.</em>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <warning>
        <p>
            The formula <term>does not</term> mention the internal chord <m>AB</m>, but the external secant <m>PB</m>. Make sure you use the full distance from <m>B</m> to <m>P</m>, not just the distance from <m>B</m> to <m>A</m>. You might have to add <m>PA</m> and <m>AB</m> to get <m>PB</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            The same applies to the second secant: use the full distance from <m>D</m> to <m>P</m>, not just the distance from <m>D</m> to <m>C</m>.
        </p>
    </warning>

    <p>
        The Two-Secant Theorem tells us that <m>PA \times PB = PC \times PD</m>. This can be understood using similar triangles: 
        
    </p>
    <figure xml:id="fig-two-secant-theorem-explain">
            <caption>Similar Triangles</caption>
            <image width="80%">
                <latex-image>
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \tkzDefPoints{0/0/P, 4/0/O}
                        \tkzDefCircle[R](O,2) \tkzGetPoint{cR}
                        \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                        \tkzDefPoint(6.5,2){S1}
                        \tkzInterLC[near](P,S1)(O,cR) \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}
                        \tkzDefPoint(6.5,-1.5){S2}
                        \tkzInterLC[near](P,S2)(O,cR) \tkzGetPoints{C}{D}
                        \tkzDrawSegments(P,B P,D A,C B,D)
                        \tkzDrawPoints(P,A,B,C,D)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[above right](B)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below left](C)
                        \tkzLabelPoints[below right](D)
                        \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, pos=0.2, font=\small](P,B){$PA$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, pos=0.55, font=\small](P,B){$PB$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, pos=0.2, font=\small](P,D){$PC$}
                        \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, pos=0.55, font=\small](P,D){$PD$}
                        \tkzFillAngle[fill=orange!20, opacity=0.5, size=0.5](C,P,A)
                        \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.5](C,P,A)
                        \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.8](C,P,A){\small $\alpha$}

                        \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!20, opacity=0.5, size=0.4](P,A,C)
                        \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.4](P,A,C)
                        \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.7](P,A,C){\small $\beta$}

                        \tkzFillAngle[fill=red!20, opacity=0.5, size=0.4](C,A,B)
                        \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.4](C,A,B)
                        \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.7, xshift=10pt](C,A,B){\small $180^\circ - \beta$}

                        \tkzFillAngle[fill=cyan!20, opacity=0.5, size=0.5](B,D,C)
                        \tkzMarkAngle[size=0.5](B,D,C)
                        \tkzLabelAngle[pos=0.9](B,D,C){\small $\beta$}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>
        </figure>
    <p>
        The triangles <m>\triangle PAD</m> and <m>\triangle PCB</m> are similar because:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    They share the angle <m>\alpha</m> at <m>P</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Since <m>ABDC</m> is a cyclic quadrilateral, we have <m>\angle BDC = 180^\circ - \angle BAC</m>. Since <m>PB</m> is a line, <m>\angle PAC = 180^\circ - \angle BAC</m>. Thus <md>
                        \angle BDC = 180^\circ - \angle BAC = \angle PAC
                    </md>
                    
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Hence the two triangles are similar by the AA criterion.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        Hence the ratios of corresponding sides are equal, so:
        <md>
            <mrow> \frac{PA}{PD} \amp = \frac{PC}{PB} </mrow>
            <mrow> PA \times PB \amp = PC \times PD </mrow>
        </md> 
    </p>

    <insight>
        <title>Special Case: Tangent-Secant Theorem</title>
        <p>
            As the points <m>C</m> and <m>D</m> move closer together, we have <m>PC \approx PD</m>. In the limit as <m>C</m> and <m>D</m> merge into a single point <m>T</m>, the second secant becomes a tangent, and the product <m>PC \times PD</m> becomes <m>PT \times PT = PT^2</m>. This gives us the Tangent-Secant Theorem, which is a special case of the Two-Secant Theorem:
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-secant-insight">
                <caption>Tangent and secant.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoint(0,0){P}
                          \tkzDefPoint(4,0){O}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefCircle[R](O,2) \tkzGetPoint{cR}
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(P,O)   \tkzGetPoint{M}
                          \tkzInterCC(M,P)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{Thigh}{T}
                          \tkzDefPoint(8,2){Sg}
                          \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                          \tkzDrawSegment(P,T)
                          \tkzDrawSegment(P,B)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](P,T,A,B)

                          %% --- MARK ---

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above right](T)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[right](B)
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](P,T){PT}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](P,A){PA}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, pos=0.6, font=\small](P,B){PB}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>
        <p>
            If a tangent and a secant are drawn to a circle from the same external point <m>P</m>, with the tangent touching at <m>T</m> and the secant meeting the circle at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, then
            <md>
                PT^2 = PA \times PB.
            </md>
            In words: <em>the square of the tangent length equals the product of the external segment and the whole secant.</em>
        </p>
    </insight>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/example-intro.ptx" />

    <example xml:id="example-two-secant-theorem">
        <title>Using the Two-Secant Theorem</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                From an external point <m>P</m>, two secants are drawn to a circle. The first secant meets the circle at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, where <m>PA = 4</m> cm and <m>AB = 9</m> cm. The second secant meets the circle at <m>C</m> and <m>D</m>, where <m>PC = 3</m> cm. Find <m>PD</m>.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="fig-two-secant-example">
                <caption>Two secants from <m>P</m>.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoint(7,0){P}
                          \tkzDefPoint(3,0){O}
                          \tkzDefPoint(5,0){cR}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefPoint(-1,2.5){Sg1}
                          \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg1)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}
                          \tkzDefPoint(-1,-2.5){Sg2}
                          \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg2)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{C}{D}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                          \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,B)
                          \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,D)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](P,A,B,C,D)

                          %% --- MARK ---

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[right](P)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above right](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above left](B)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](C)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](D)
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](P,A){$4$ cm}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, pos=0.75, font=\small](P,B){$8$ cm}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, font=\small](P,C){$3$ cm}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since we are only told <m>PA</m> and <m>AB</m>, we calculate <m>PB = PA + PB = 4 + 8 = 12</m>
                By the Two-Secant Theorem:
                <md>
                    <mrow> PA \times PB \amp = PC \times PD </mrow>
                    <mrow> 4 \times 12 \amp = 3 \times PD </mrow>
                    <mrow>PD \amp = 16 \text{\, cm} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                Note that the chord <m>CD</m> inside the circle has length <m>PD - PC = 16 - 3 = 13</m> cm.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-tangent-secant-theorem">
        <title>Using the Tangent-Secant Theorem</title>
        <statement>
            <p>
                From an external point <m>P</m>, a tangent <m>PT</m> is drawn to a circle, touching it at <m>T</m>. A secant from <m>P</m> meets the circle at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, where <m>PA = 4</m> cm is the external segment. Given that <m>PT = 6</m> cm, find the length <m>PB</m> and the length of the chord <m>AB</m>.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-secant-example">
                <caption>Tangent <m>PT = 6</m> cm from external point <m>P</m>; secant with external segment <m>PA = 4</m> cm.</caption>
                <image width="60%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoint(0,0){P}
                          \tkzDefPoint(5,0){O}
                          \tkzDefPoint(7,0){cR}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(P,O)   \tkzGetPoint{M}
                          \tkzInterCC(M,P)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{T}{Tlow}
                          \tkzDefPoint(8,-1.5){Sg}
                          \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                          \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,T)
                          \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,B)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](P,T,A,B)

                          %% --- MARK ---

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above right](T)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)
                          \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](P,T){$6$ cm}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, font=\small](P,A){$4$ cm}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                By the Tangent-Secant Theorem:
                <md>
                    <mrow> PT^2 \amp = PA \times PB </mrow>
                    <mrow> 6^2 \amp = 4 \times PB </mrow>
                    <mrow> 36 \amp = 4 \times PB </mrow>
                    <mrow> PB \amp = \frac{36}{4} = 9 \text{ cm.} </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>
                The chord <m>AB</m> lies inside the circle, so its length is:
                <md>
                    AB = PB - PA = 9 - 4 = 5 \text{ cm.}
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="example-equal-tangents-combined">
        <statement>
            <p>
                In <xref ref="fig-secant-quadratic"/>, a tangent from <m>A</m> meets a secant through <m>F</m> and <m>E</m> at <m>T</m>, with <m>AT = 4 \,\text{cm}</m> and <m>FE = 6\,\text{cm}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Find the distance <m>TF</m>.
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="fig-secant-quadratic">
                <caption>Tangent and a Secant</caption>
                <image width="55%">
                    <latex-image>
                        \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                          %% --- SET ---
                          \tkzDefPoint(6,1){T}
                          \tkzDefPoint(3,4){O}
                          \tkzDefPoint(5,4){cR}

                          %% --- CALCULATE ---
                          \tkzDefMidPoint(T,O)   \tkzGetPoint{M}
                          \tkzInterCC(M,T)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}
                          \tkzDefPoint(2,7){Sg}
                          \tkzInterLC[near](T,Sg)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{E}{F}

                          %% --- DRAW ---
                          \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                          \tkzDrawSegments[thick](T,A)
                          \tkzDrawSegment[thick](T,F)
                          \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](T,A,E,F)

                          %% --- MARK ---

                          %% --- LABEL ---
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below](T)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[left](E)
                          \tkzLabelPoints[above left](F)
                          \tkzLabelSegment[below left, font=\small](T,A){$4$ cm}
                          \tkzLabelSegment[left, font=\small](F,E){$6$ cm}

                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </figure>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Let <m>TE = x\,\text{cm}</m>, which makes <m>TF = TE + EF = x + 6</m>. By the Tangent-Secant Theorem we have:
                <md>
                    <mrow>AT^2 \amp = TE \times TF</mrow>
                    <mrow>16 \amp = x(x+6)</mrow>
                    <mrow>x^2 + 6x - 16 \amp = 0</mrow>
                    <mrow>(x+8)(x-2) \amp = 0</mrow>
                </md>
                As distances must be positive, we have <m>x = 2\,\text{cm}</m> as the only option. This gives <m>TF = x + 6 = 8\, \text{cm}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <xi:include href="../lesson-plan-templates/assessment-intro.ptx" />

    <exercises>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-two-secants-find-segment">
            <statement>
                <p>
                    From an external point <m>P</m>, two secants are drawn to a circle.
                    <ul>
                        <li><p>The first secant meets the circle at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, with <m>PA = 2</m> cm and <m>PB = 9</m> cm.</p></li>
                        <li><p>The second secant meets the circle at <m>C</m> and <m>D</m>, with <m>PC = 3</m> cm.</p></li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-two-secants-exercise">
                    <caption>Two secants from <m>P</m> below the circle: first meeting at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>; second meeting at <m>C</m> and <m>D</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoint(5,1.5){P}
                              \tkzDefPoint(4,4.5){O}
                              \tkzDefPoint(6,4.5){cR}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefPoint(1,7){Sg1}
                              \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg1)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}
                              \tkzDefPoint(5,7){Sg2}
                              \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg2)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{C}{D}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,B)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,D)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](P,A,B,C,D)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below](P)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above left](B)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[right](C)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above right](D)
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below left, font=\small](P,A){$2$ cm}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above right, font=\small](P,B){$9$ cm}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above right, font=\small](P,C){$3$ cm}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>Find <m>PD</m>.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Find the length of chord <m>CD</m>.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p> We have:
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> PA \times PB \amp = PC \times PD </mrow>
                                    <mrow> 2 \times 9 \amp = 3 \times PD </mrow> 
                                    <mrow> PD \amp = 6 \text{\, cm}</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>CD = PD - PC = 6 - 3 = 3</m> cm.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-tangent-secant-find-tangent">
            <title>Finding a Tangent Length</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A secant from external point <m>P</m> meets a circle at <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, where <m>PA = 4</m> cm and the chord <m>AB = 12</m> cm. A tangent from <m>P</m> touches the circle at <m>T</m>. Find the length <m>PT</m>.
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="fig-find-tangent-exercise">
                    <caption>Secant from <m>P</m> with external segment <m>PA = 4</m> cm and chord <m>AB = 12</m> cm; tangent from <m>P</m> to <m>T</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoint(7,5){P}
                              \tkzDefPoint(3,2){O}
                              \tkzDefPoint(5,2){cR}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefMidPoint(P,O)   \tkzGetPoint{M}
                              \tkzInterCC(M,P)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{T}{Tsec}
                              \tkzDefPoint(1,0){Sg}
                              \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,T)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,B)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](P,T,A,B)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above right](P)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above left](T)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](B)
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](P,A){$4$ cm}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](A,B){$12$ cm}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

            </statement>
            <hint>
                <p>
                    First find <m>PB</m> using <m>PB = PA + AB</m>, then apply the Tangent-Secant Theorem.
                </p>
            </hint>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>PB = PA + AB = 4 + 12 = 16</m> cm.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>PT^2 = PA \times PB = 4 \times 16 = 64</m>, so <m>PT = 8</m> cm.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-equal-tangents-algebra">
            <title>Equal Tangents</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Two tangents are drawn from an external point <m>Q</m> to a circle. The tangent lengths are <m>QR = 3x - 2</m> and <m>QS = x + 6</m>. Find the value of <m>x</m> and the length of each tangent.
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="fig-equal-tangents-exercise">
                    <caption>Two tangents from external point <m>Q</m> touching the circle at <m>R</m> and <m>S</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoint(7,-1){Q}
                              \tkzDefPoint(2.5,3){O}
                              \tkzDefPoint(4.5,3){cR}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefMidPoint(Q,O)   \tkzGetPoint{M}
                              \tkzInterCC(M,Q)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{R}{S}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                              \tkzDrawSegments[thick](Q,R Q,S)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](Q,R,S)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](Q)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above left](R)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above right](S)
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](Q,R){$3x-2$}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, font=\small](Q,S){$x+6$}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>3x - 2 = x + 6 \Rightarrow 2x = 8 \Rightarrow x = 4</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Each tangent has length <m>QR = 3(4) - 2 = 10</m> cm.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-find-chord-from-tangent">
            <title>Finding a Chord from a Known Tangent</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    From an external point <m>P</m>, a tangent <m>PT = 10</m> cm is drawn to a circle. A secant from <m>P</m> has an external segment <m>PA = 4</m> cm.
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="fig-chord-from-tangent-exercise">
                    <caption>Tangent <m>PT = 10</m> cm and secant with external segment <m>PA = 4</m> cm from external point <m>P</m>.</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoint(0,0){P}
                              \tkzDefPoint(5,3.5){O}
                              \tkzDefPoint(7,3.5){cR}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefMidPoint(P,O)   \tkzGetPoint{M}
                              \tkzInterCC(M,P)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{T}{Tsec}
                              \tkzDefPoint(8,3){Sg}
                              \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,T)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,B)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](P,T,A,B)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above](T)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below left](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[right](B)
                              \tkzLabelSegment[above, sloped, font=\small](P,T){$10$ cm}
                              \tkzLabelSegment[below, sloped, font=\small](P,A){$4$ cm}

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li><p>Find the full length <m>PB</m> of the secant.</p></li>
                        <li><p>Find the length of the chord <m>AB</m> inside the circle.</p></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>PT^2 = PA \times PB \Rightarrow 100 = 4 \times PB \Rightarrow PB = 25</m> cm.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                <m>AB = PB - PA = 25 - 4 = 21</m> cm.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="exercise-secant-tangent-reasoning">
            <title>Reasoning with Similar Triangles</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The diagram below shows a circle with external point <m>P</m>. A tangent from <m>P</m> touches the circle at <m>T</m>, and a secant from <m>P</m> meets the circle at <m>A</m> (nearer) and <m>B</m> (farther).
                </p>

                <figure xml:id="fig-tangent-secant-exercise">
                    <caption>External point <m>P</m>, tangent to <m>T</m>, secant through <m>A</m> (nearer) and <m>B</m> (farther).</caption>
                    <image width="55%">
                        <latex-image>
                            \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.0]

                              %% --- SET ---
                              \tkzDefPoint(0,0){P}
                              \tkzDefPoint(5,0){O}
                              \tkzDefPoint(7,0){cR}

                              %% --- CALCULATE ---
                              \tkzDefMidPoint(P,O)   \tkzGetPoint{M}
                              \tkzInterCC(M,P)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{T}{Tlow}
                              \tkzDefPoint(8,-1.5){Sg}
                              \tkzInterLC[near](P,Sg)(O,cR)   \tkzGetPoints{A}{B}

                              %% --- DRAW ---
                              \tkzDrawCircle[thick, teal](O,cR)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,T)
                              \tkzDrawSegment[thick](P,B)
                              \tkzDrawPoints[size=2pt](P,T,A,B)

                              %% --- MARK ---

                              %% --- LABEL ---
                              \tkzLabelPoints[left](P)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[above right](T)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below](A)
                              \tkzLabelPoints[below right](B)

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>

                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Write down the size of angle <m>\angle PTA</m>. (<em>Hint:</em> what is the angle between a tangent and a radius?)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                In triangle <m>\triangle PTB</m> and triangle <m>\triangle PAT</m>, identify the angle they share and explain why <m>\angle PTB = \angle TAB</m>. (This follows from the tangent-chord angle theorem — the angle between a tangent and a chord equals the inscribed angle on the opposite side.)
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Explain why <m>\triangle PTB \sim \triangle PAT</m>, and use this to show that <m>PT^2 = PA \times PB</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                The radius <m>OT</m> is perpendicular to the tangent at <m>T</m>. However, <m>\angle PTA</m> is not a right angle in general — it is the tangent-chord angle. The angle between the tangent <m>PT</m> and chord <m>TA</m> equals the inscribed angle in the alternate segment, i.e. <m>\angle PTA = \angle TBA</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Both triangles share the angle at <m>P</m>. By the tangent-chord angle theorem, <m>\angle PTB = \angle TAB</m> (tangent-chord angle equals inscribed angle in alternate segment).
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Since <m>\triangle PTB</m> and <m>\triangle PAT</m> share angle <m>P</m> and have <m>\angle PTB = \angle PAT</m> (= inscribed angle in alternate segment), they are similar by AA. From the ratio of corresponding sides:
                                <md>
                                    \frac{PT}{PB} = \frac{PA}{PT},
                                </md>
                                which gives <m>PT^2 = PA \times PB</m>.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

    </exercises>

